'''Dean Bradley Henderson''' (born 12 March 1997) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for {{English football updater|CrystalP}} club [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], whom he [[Captain (association football)|captains]], and the [[England national football team|England national team]].

Henderson joined [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester United's youth system]] in 2011 from [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]]. Between 2015 and 2020, he was [[Loan (association football)|loaned]] out to a number of teams across divisions, before making his Premier League debut with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in 2019. After returning to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]'s first team and making his debut in 2020, he spent two seasons making sporadic appearances as a back-up.

After a season on loan at [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], Henderson was signed permanently by Crystal Palace in 2023, where he won the [[2024–25 FA Cup|FA Cup]] and [[2025 FA Community Shield|Community Shield]] in 2025. He was appointed club captain in 2026, leading his side to win the [[2025–26 UEFA Conference League|UEFA Conference League]] the same year.

Henderson has represented England at [[England national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[England national under-20 football team|under-20]], [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] and senior levels. He was a member of the England under-20 squad that won the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]], and the senior team that were runners-up at [[UEFA Euro 2020]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024]].

==Club career==
===Manchester United===
Henderson joined the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester United academy]] aged 14, having spent six years at [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]].<ref name="Henderson 1">{{cite web |title=Dean Henderson |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/Reserves/Dean-Henderson.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |access-date=26 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525182303/http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/Reserves/Dean-Henderson.aspx |archive-date=25 May 2018}}</ref> He first joined the academy in August 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Fanzone/News-And-Blogs/2011/Aug/The-Gossip-week-11.aspx?pageNo=12 |title=The Gossip Week |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=8 August 2011 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525175101/http://www.manutd.com/en/Fanzone/News-And-Blogs/2011/Aug/The-Gossip-week-11.aspx?pageNo=12 |archive-date=25 May 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>

After progressing through the academy, Henderson was among 10 players to join the academy squad for the 2013–14 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/The-Academy/Academy-News/2013/Jun/~/link.aspx?_id=E6AD3BF0C00F41369EA93F29716E66C6&_z=z |title=Reds sign up first-years |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=30 June 2013 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525182916/http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/The-Academy/Academy-News/2013/Jun/~/link.aspx?_id=E6AD3BF0C00F41369EA93F29716E66C6&_z=z |archive-date=25 May 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> He became a regular goalkeeper for the U18 team in the 2013–14 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Features/2013/Dec/manchester-united-youth-team-2013-2014-pen-pics.aspx?_id=C5DB37B60CCA4FA29EA84ECC13A6980B&_z=z&pageNo=1 |title=United's Youth Cup squad |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=18 December 2013 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525184338/http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Features/2013/Dec/manchester-united-youth-team-2013-2014-pen-pics.aspx?_id=C5DB37B60CCA4FA29EA84ECC13A6980B&_z=z&pageNo=1 |archive-date=25 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

In the 2014–15 season, Henderson continued to impress as a regular goalkeeper for the U18 team, as he made 25 appearances but sustained an injury towards the end of the season.<ref name="Henderson 2"/> Nevertheless, he was among nominees for the Jimmy Murphy Young Player of the Year award but lost out to [[Axel Tuanzebe]].<ref name="Henderson 1"/> In August 2015, Henderson signed his first professional contract with the club.<ref>{{cite web |last=Peoples |first=Sam |date=25 August 2015 |title=Dean Henderson signs new Manchester United contract |url=https://thepeoplesperson.com/2015/08/25/dean-henderson-signs-new-man-united-contract-116358/ |access-date=26 May 2018 |website=The Peoples Person}}</ref>

====2016: Loan to Stockport County====
On 12 January 2016, he was [[Loan (association football)|loaned]] to [[National League North]] club [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] on an initial one-month loan.<ref>{{cite web |title=United keeper to sign for the Hatters |url=http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/dean-henderson-joins-county-2889320.aspx |publisher=Stockport County F.C. |date=12 January 2016 |access-date=26 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227061416/http://www.stockportcounty.com/news/article/dean-henderson-joins-county-2889320.aspx |archive-date=27 December 2016}}</ref> He made his Stockport County debut, where he played the whole game, in a 1–1 draw against [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Town]] on 16 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nuneatontownfc.com/teams/98603/match-centre/1-1591111 |title=Match Report: Stockport County 1 Nuneaton Town 1 |publisher=Nuneaton Town F.C. |date=16 January 2016 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160213200332/http://www.nuneatontownfc.com/teams/98603/match-centre/1-1591111 |archive-date=13 February 2016}}</ref>

On 22 February 2016, due to an injury crisis, Henderson was recalled from loan and had his first call-up to a senior [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] game, sitting on the bench during a 3–0 [[FA Cup]] victory away to [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dawson |first1=Rob |title=Dean Henderson set for place in Manchester United squad to face Shrewsbury |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/dean-henderson-set-place-manchester-10922228 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=20 February 2016 |access-date=26 December 2016}}<br />{{cite news |title=Shrewsbury Town 0–3 Manchester United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35576165 |website=BBC Sport |date=22 February 2016 |access-date=26 December 2016}}</ref> Henderson then returned to Stockport County to complete his loan spell.<ref>{{cite news |title=PREVIEW: North Ferriby United v Stockport County |url=http://quaysnews.net/index.php/2016/03/25/preview-north-ferriby-united-v-stockport-county/ |newspaper=Quays News |date=25 March 2016 |access-date=27 December 2016 |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228032350/http://quaysnews.net/index.php/2016/03/25/preview-north-ferriby-united-v-stockport-county/ |archive-date=28 December 2016}}</ref> His first game after signing for the club for the second time was a 2–0 loss against [[North Ferriby United A.F.C.|North Ferriby United]] on 26 March 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Ferriby United end Stockport County's unbeaten run |url=http://quaysnews.net/index.php/2016/03/26/north-ferriby-united-end-stockport-countys-unbeaten-run/ |newspaper=Quays News |date=26 March 2016 |access-date=26 May 2018 |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525193735/http://quaysnews.net/index.php/2016/03/26/north-ferriby-united-end-stockport-countys-unbeaten-run/ |archive-date=25 May 2018}}</ref> He went on to make nine appearances for Stockport County and kept three clean sheets.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradford Park Avenue and Stockport County share goalless draw |url=http://quaysnews.net/index.php/2016/02/13/rbradford-park-avenue-and-stockport-county-share-goalless-draw/ |newspaper=Quays News |date=13 February 2016 |access-date=26 May 2018 |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525194841/http://quaysnews.net/index.php/2016/02/13/rbradford-park-avenue-and-stockport-county-share-goalless-draw/ |archive-date=25 May 2018}}<br />{{cite news |title=Stockport County and Curzon Ashton play out dull end of season draw |url=http://quaysnews.net/index.php/2016/04/30/report-stockport-county-v-curzon-ashton/ |newspaper=Quays News |date=30 April 2016 |access-date=26 May 2018 |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525194633/http://quaysnews.net/index.php/2016/04/30/report-stockport-county-v-curzon-ashton/ |archive-date=25 May 2018}}</ref>

====2016–2017: Loan to Grimsby Town====
On 31 August 2016, Henderson joined [[EFL League Two|League Two]] club [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] on loan until the beginning of January 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dean Henderson leaves Manchester United for Grimsby Town loan |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11769/10560071/dean-henderson-leaves-manchester-united-for-grimsby-town-loan |date=31 August 2016 |access-date=26 December 2016 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=31 August 2016 |title=Grimsby Town: Shaun Tuton, Dean Henderson and Brandon Comley join League Two club |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37230580 |access-date=13 April 2025 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref> However, he started his Grimsby Town career as second–choice goalkeeper behind [[James McKeown]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Dawson |first=Rob |date=26 September 2016 |title=How are Manchester United loan stars Januzaj, Pereira and the rest getting on? |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-utd-loans-januzaj-pereira-11940368 |access-date=26 May 2018 |website=Manchester Evening News}}</ref> Henderson made his debut on 26 December 2016, in a 2–0 victory over [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] at [[Blundell Park]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/2016/december/grimsby-town-2-0-accrington-stanley/ |title=Match Reports: Grimsby Town 2–0 Accrington Stanley |publisher=Grimsby Town F.C. |date=26 December 2016 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525204557/https://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/2016/december/grimsby-town-2-0-accrington-stanley/ |archive-date=25 May 2018 |url-status=usurped}}</ref> After making his debut, his performance was praised by Manager [[Marcus Bignot]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/2016/december/bignot-an-important-result/ |title=Bignot: An Important Result |publisher=Grimsby Town F.C. |date=26 December 2016 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525203810/https://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/2016/december/bignot-an-important-result/ |archive-date=25 May 2018 |url-status=usurped}}</ref> On 31 December 2016, Henderson had his loan at Grimsby Town extended until the end of January 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Henderson extends loan at Grimsby |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2016/Dec/manchester-united-goalkeeper-Dean-Henderson-loan-extended-at-grimsby-town-until-end-of-January.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=31 December 2016 |access-date=1 January 2017}}<br />{{cite web |title=Dean Henderson extends Town stay |url=http://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/dean-henderson-extends-manchester-united-loan-3492627.aspx |publisher=Grimsby Town F.C. |date=31 December 2016 |access-date=1 January 2017 |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103190350/http://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/dean-henderson-extends-manchester-united-loan-3492627.aspx |archive-date=3 January 2017}}</ref> On the same day, he kept another clean sheet, in a 0–0 draw against [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/2016/december/report-grimsby-town-v-blackpool/ |title=REPORT: Grimsby Town v Blackpool |publisher=Grimsby Town F.C. |date=31 December 2016 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525210556/https://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/2016/december/report-grimsby-town-v-blackpool/ |archive-date=25 May 2018 |url-status=usurped}}</ref>

It was then extended again on 25 January 2017, until the end of the 2016–17 season.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rej |first=Arindam |date=26 January 2017 |title=Manchester United's Dean Henderson extends loan spell with Grimsby |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/37511564/manchester-united-dean-henderson-extends-loan-spell-grimsby |access-date=3 February 2017 |website=ESPN}}</ref> However, Manchester United recalled Henderson from the loan spell on 3 February 2017, due to an injury to third-choice goalkeeper [[Joel Castro Pereira]].<ref>{{cite web |date=3 February 2017 |title=Man United recall Dean Henderson from Grimsby after Joel Pereira injury |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/37512418/manchester-united-recall-dean-henderson-grimsby-joel-pereira-injury |access-date=3 February 2017 |website=ESPN}}</ref> By the time of his departure, Henderson made seven appearances and kept four clean sheets; he had become the first-choice goalkeeper.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/2017/february/henderson-recalled-by-manchester-united/ |title=Henderson Recalled By Manchester United |publisher=Grimsby Town F.C. |date=3 February 2017 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525210546/https://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/2017/february/henderson-recalled-by-manchester-united/ |archive-date=25 May 2018 |url-status=usurped}}</ref>

====2017–2018: Loan to Shrewsbury Town====
On 10 July 2017, Henderson joined [[EFL League One|League One]] club Shrewsbury Town on loan for the [[2017–18 Shrewsbury Town F.C. season|2017–18 season]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Dean Henderson joins Shrewsbury on loan |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2017/Jul/dean-henderson-manchester-united-goalkeeper-joins-shrewsbury-town-on-loan-for-2017-18-season.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=10 July 2017 |access-date=10 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115231119/http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2017/Jul/dean-henderson-manchester-united-goalkeeper-joins-shrewsbury-town-on-loan-for-2017-18-season.aspx |archive-date=15 November 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=10 July 2017 |title=Dean Henderson: Manchester United goalkeeper joins Shrewsbury Town on loan |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40562359 |access-date=13 April 2025 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ullal |first=Naveen |title=Manchester United goalkeeper Dean Henderson completes loan move to Shrewsbury Town |url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/manchester-united-goalkeeper-dean-henderson-completes-loan-move-shrewsbury-town-1629750 |access-date=13 April 2025 |website=International Business Times UK |date=11 July 2017 }}</ref> Upon joining the club, Henderson was given a number 1 shirt ahead of the new season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.shrewsburytown.com/news/2017/july/squad-numbers/ |title=Squad Numbers |publisher=Shrewsbury Town F.C. |date=31 July 2017 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526192418/https://www.shrewsburytown.com/news/2017/july/squad-numbers/ |archive-date=26 May 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Henderson made his Shrewsbury Town debut, in the opening game of the season, where he kept a clean sheet, in a 1–0 win over [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]].<ref>{{cite news |date=5 August 2017 |title=Shrewsbury Town 1–0 Northampton Town |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40761035 |access-date=26 May 2018 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He also kept another clean sheet in a follow–up match, in a 1–0 win over [[AFC Wimbledon]].<ref>{{cite news |date=12 August 2017 |title=AFC Wimbledon 0–1 Shrewsbury Town |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40834867 |access-date=26 May 2018 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> Henderson quickly established himself as the club's first choice goalkeeper and became the club's fan favourite.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cox |first=Lewis |date=8 September 2017 |title=No pressure from Manchester United to pick Dean Henderson |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2017/09/08/no-pressure-from-manchester-united-to-pick-dean-henderson/ |access-date=26 May 2018 |website=Shropshire Star}}</ref> He has also helped the club win the number of matches to help them go to the top of the table.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cox |first=Lewis |date=26 September 2017 |title=Dean Henderson: Shrewsbury Town have the hunger to stay top |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2017/09/26/dean-henderson-weve-the-hunger-to-stay-top/ |access-date=26 May 2018 |website=Shropshire Star}}</ref> By September, Henderson reflected his time at the club so far, saying he enjoyed playing football there and playing Saturday/Tuesday is excellent for his development.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.shrewsburytown.com/news/2017/september/dean-henderson-pre-doncaster-rovers/ |title=Dean Henderson Pre Doncaster Rovers |publisher=Shrewsbury Town F.C. |date=26 September 2017 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526201637/https://www.shrewsburytown.com/news/2017/september/dean-henderson-pre-doncaster-rovers/ |archive-date=26 May 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>

By December, there were rumours when his parent club may recall Henderson in January.<ref>{{cite web |last=Edwards |first=Joe |date=15 December 2017 |title=Manchester United delighted with Dean Henderson's Shrewsbury Town displays |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2017/12/15/manchester-united-delighted-with-dean-hendersons-shrewsbury-town-displays/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405194959/https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2017/12/15/manchester-united-delighted-with-dean-hendersons-shrewsbury-town-displays/ |archive-date=5 April 2023 |access-date=26 May 2018 |website=Shropshire Star}}</ref> Later that month, Henderson kept three clean sheets in three matches against Blackpool, [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] and [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Shrewsbury Town 1 Blackpool 0 – Report and pictures |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2017/12/16/shrewsbury-town-1-blackpool-0---report-and-pictures/ |newspaper=Shropshire Star |date=16 December 2017 |access-date=26 May 2018 }}<br />{{cite news |title=Shrewsbury Town 2 Portsmouth 0 – Report and pictures |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2017/12/23/shrewsbury-town-2-portsmouth-0---report-and-pictures/ |newspaper=Shropshire Star |date=23 December 2017 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-date=5 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405065452/https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2017/12/23/shrewsbury-town-2-portsmouth-0---report-and-pictures/ |url-status=dead }}<br />{{cite news |title=Wigan 0 Shrewsbury Town 0 – Report and pictures |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2017/12/26/wigan-0-shrewsbury-town-0---report-and-pictures/ |newspaper=Shropshire Star |date=26 December 2017 |access-date=26 May 2018 }}</ref> However, Henderson served a three match suspension after being involved in an altercation with an opposition supporter during a 3–1 loss against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on 13 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last=Maher |first=Matt |date=26 January 2018 |title=Shrewsbury Town goalkeeper Dean Henderson hit by shock three-game ban |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2018/01/26/shrewsbury-town-goalkeeper-dean-henderson-hit-by-shock-three-game-ban/ |access-date=26 May 2018 |website=Shropshire Star}}</ref> Initially the club made a decision to appeal, the club changed their mind shortly after.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shrewsbury Town weighing up Dean Henderson appeal |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2018/01/27/shrewsbury-town-weighing-up-dean-henderson-appeal/ |newspaper=Shropshire Star |date=27 January 2018 |access-date=26 May 2018}}<br />{{cite news |title=Shrewsbury Town decide against appealing Dean Henderson ban |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2018/01/30/shrewsbury-town-decide-against-appealing-dean-henderson-ban/ |newspaper=Shropshire Star |date=30 January 2018 |access-date=26 May 2018}}</ref> After serving a three match ban, Henderson returned to the starting line-up on 13 February 2018, in a 2–1 win over [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]].<ref>{{cite news |date=13 February 2018 |title=Fleetwood Town 1–2 Shrewsbury Town |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42955231 |access-date=26 May 2018 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> By the end of March, Henderson kept 13 clean sheets for the team.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cox |first=Lewis |date=27 March 2018 |title=Assistant Chris Doig backs Shrewsbury's Dean Henderson to reach the very top |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2018/03/27/assistant-chris-doig-backs-shrewsburys-dean-henderson-to-reach-the-very-top/ |access-date=26 May 2018 |website=Shropshire Star}}</ref>

On 8 April 2018, he played at [[Wembley Stadium]] in the [[2018 EFL Trophy final]] against [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]], which Shrewsbury Town lost 1–0, and later that month was one of only three players not from Wigan Athletic or Blackburn Rovers to be selected for the League One [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)|PFA Team of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Cox |first=Lewis |date=8 April 2018 |title=Checkatrade Trophy final: Shrewsbury 0 Lincoln 1 – Report and pictures |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2018/04/08/checkatrade-trophy-final-shrewsbury-0-lincoln-1---report-and-pictures/ |access-date=26 May 2018 |website=Shropshire Star}}</ref><ref name="1718PFA">{{cite news |date=18 April 2018 |title=PFA League One Team of the Year: Wigan & Blackburn quartets included |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43808541 |access-date=5 May 2018 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> The following month, in the [[2018 English Football League play-offs#League One Semi-finals|League One play-offs]], Henderson kept two clean sheets in a 2–0 win over [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] on aggregate to reach the [[2018 EFL League One play-off final|final]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Cartwright |first=Phil |date=10 May 2018 |title=Charlton Athletic 0–1 Shrewsbury Town |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44019731 |access-date=26 May 2018 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cartwright |first=Phil |date=13 May 2018 |title=Shrewsbury Town 1–0 Charlton Athletic (Agg 2–0) |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44020111 |access-date=26 May 2018 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> Henderson started in goal in the final when [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] beat Shrewsbury Town 2–1 after extra time, and he saved a penalty from [[David Ball (footballer)|David Ball]] after nine minutes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Scott |first=Ged |date=27 May 2018 |title=Rotherham United 2–1 Shrewsbury Town (AET) |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44186999 |access-date=31 May 2018 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

Henderson made two separate statements, expressing his gratitude and admiration for the club, and his hope to one day return in the future.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hatfield |first=Luke |date=28 May 2018 |title=Dean Henderson issues heartfelt goodbye to Shrewsbury Town fans |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2018/05/28/dean-henderson-issues-heartfelt-goodbye-to-shrewsbury-town-fans/ |access-date=31 May 2018 |website=Shropshire Star}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Cox |first=Lewis |date=17 May 2018 |title=It's Shrew love for Town keeper Dean Henderson |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/football/shrewsbury-town-fc/2018/05/17/its-shrew-love-for-town-keeper-dean-henderson/ |access-date=26 May 2018 |website=Shropshire Star}}</ref>

====2018–2020: Loans to Sheffield United====
[[FILE:DeanHenderson2018.jpg|thumb|upright|Henderson playing for [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in 2018]]

In June 2018, Henderson signed a two-year contract extension with his parent club, which was due to expire in June 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fay |first=Richard |date=14 June 2018 |title=Manchester United goalkeeper signs new contract at the club |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/man-utd-henderson-contract-transfer-14787020 |access-date=20 June 2018 |website=Manchester Evening News}}</ref> On 18 June, he joined [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] on loan until the end of the 2018–19 season,<ref>{{cite news |title=Dean Henderson: Manchester United keeper joins Sheffield United on loan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44525272 |website=BBC Sport |date=18 June 2018 |access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> helping them to secure promotion to the [[Premier League]] for the first time since 2007.<ref>{{cite news |date=28 April 2019 |title=Sheffield United promoted to Premier League after Leeds draw |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48026965 |access-date=30 April 2019 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref> During his season-long loan, Henderson won the club's Young Player of the Year Award,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sufc.co.uk/news/2019/april/mcgoldrick-scoops-top-award/ |title=McGoldrick scoops top award |publisher=Sheffield United F.C.}}</ref> as well as the Championship Golden Glove<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sufc.co.uk/news/2019/may/golden-glove-for-deano/ |title=Golden Glove for Deano |publisher=Sheffield United F.C.}}</ref> keeping 20 clean sheets across the season. Following an impressive debut season in the championship, European giants [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] and [[Juventus FC|Juventus]] had reported interest in the goalkeeper.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dawnay |first=Oliver |date=1 May 2019 |title=What those in the know say about Dean Henderson, including Wilder and Southgate |url=https://talksport.com/football/535951/dean-henderson-what-those-in-the-know-say-manchester-uniteds-loan-star-shining-at-sheffield-united/ |access-date=23 July 2020 |website=TalkSport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Bacon |first=Jake |date=7 February 2019 |title=European giants 'keeping tabs' on Manchester United youngster |url=https://talksport.com/football/489877/bayern-munich-juventus-manchester-united-dean-henderson/ |access-date=23 July 2020 |website=TalkSport |language=en-gb}}</ref>

On 25 July 2019, Henderson signed a new contract with Manchester United until June 2022 and returned on loan to Sheffield United.<ref>{{cite news |title=Henderson signs new deal and goes on loan |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/dean-henderson-signs-new-man-utd-deal-and-joins-sheff-utd-on-loan |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=26 July 2019 |access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> He made his Premier League debut on 10 August as they began the season with a 1–1 draw at [[AFC Bournemouth]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Prentki |first=Tom |date=10 August 2019 |title=Billy Sharp rescues late point for Sheffield United at Bournemouth |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/08/10/billy-sharp-rescues-late-point-sheffield-united-bournemouth/ |access-date=29 September 2019 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> On 28 September against Liverpool at [[Bramall Lane]], he fumbled a shot from [[Georginio Wijnaldum]] for the game's only goal in the 70th minute. His manager [[Chris Wilder]] warned him that he would have to do better to succeed for Manchester United or England.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Banks |first1=Marcus |title=Chris Wilder fires warning to Dean Henderson over long-term Manchester United future |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/henderson-wilder-man-utd-warning-16998638 |access-date=29 September 2019 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=28 September 2019}}</ref> On 7 March, Henderson made a triple save, labelled "heroic" by [[Sky Sports]], keeping out a [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] goal in a 1–0 victory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/watch/video/sports/football/11952201/hendersons-heroic-double-save|title=Henderson's heroic triple save|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> Henderson received praise again during Sheffield United's first game following [[2019–20 Premier League#Effects of the COVID-19 pandemic|project restart]] where he kept his 11th clean sheet of the season, making six saves in the process. Following the match, Manchester United manager [[Ole Gunnar Solskjær]] confirmed that he sees Henderson as the club's future number one goalkeeper.<ref>{{cite web |last=Coombs |first=Dan |date=18 June 2020 |title=Manchester United fans react to Dean Henderson's performance |url=https://www.unitedinfocus.com/news/manchester-united-fans-react-to-dean-hendersons-performance/ |access-date=23 July 2020 |website=United In Focus |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Man Utd fans make Dean Henderson prediction after Sheffield United draw with Aston Villa |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/1297373/Man-Utd-News-Dean-Henderson-Sheffield-United-Aston-Villa-Fans-Twitter-Gossip/ |access-date=23 July 2020 |website=[[Daily Express]] |date=17 June 2020 }}</ref>

====2020–2022: Manchester United first team====
[[File:Manchester United v West Ham United, 22 September 2021 (12).jpg|thumb|Henderson (far right), in goal for Manchester United against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]], 22 September 2021]]
On 14 August 2020, Henderson was added to Manchester United's senior squad list for the first time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/man-utd-dean-henderson-news-18768546|title=Man United add Dean Henderson to first-team goalkeeper list|first=Richard|last=Fay|date=14 August 2020|access-date=14 August 2020|newspaper=Manchester Evening News}}</ref> On 26 August, he signed a new long-term contract that would keep him at Manchester United until June 2025.<ref>{{cite web |date=26 August 2020 |title=Dean Henderson signs new contract with Manchester United |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/dean-henderson-signs-new-contract-with-manchester-united |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241202112358/https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/dean-henderson-signs-new-contract-with-manchester-united |archive-date=2 December 2024 |access-date=27 August 2020 |website=Manchester United}}</ref> He made his senior debut in September in the third round of the [[2020–21 EFL Cup|League Cup]] against [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]], keeping a clean sheet in the process during United's 3–0 win.<ref>{{cite news |date=22 September 2020 |title=Luton 0–3 Manchester United: Dean Henderson thrilled with "unbelievable" debut |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54190604 |access-date=22 September 2020 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref> He made his second appearance for United a week later in the fourth round of the League Cup, keeping another clean sheet in a 3–0 victory over [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=Dawkes |title=Brighton 0–3 Man Utd: Paul Pogba strikes as United reach Carabao Cup quarters |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54298218 |website=BBC Sport |date=30 September 2020 |access-date=30 September 2020}}</ref> On 4 November, Henderson made his [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] debut for United in a 2–1 [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]] away defeat to [[İstanbul Başakşehir F.K.|İstanbul Başakşehir]].<ref>{{Cite news|first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |title=Istanbul Basaksehir 2–1 Man Utd: Demba Ba, Edin Visca, Anthony Martial score |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54799454|website=BBC Sport |date=4 November 2020 |access-date=4 November 2020}}</ref> Twenty-five days later, he made his league debut for the club as a substitute for the injured [[David de Gea]] in a 3–2 away win over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Southampton 2–3 Man Utd: Sub Edinson Cavani inspires comeback win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55032760 |website=BBC Sport |date=29 November 2020 |access-date=30 November 2020}}</ref>

In March 2021, with first choice goalkeeper [[David de Gea]] away on [[paternity leave]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Billy |first=Red |date=5 March 2021 |title=Ole Gunnar Solskjaer confirms David de Gea on paternity leave |url=https://thepeoplesperson.com/2021/03/05/ole-gunnar-solskjaer-city-presser-222445/ |access-date=8 September 2024 |website=Man United News And Transfer News {{!}} The Peoples Person |language=en-US}}</ref> Henderson was given the start against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on 3 March.<ref name=":1">{{cite web |title=Match report Crystal Palace v Man Utd Premier League 3 March 2021 |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-crystal-palace-v-man-utd-premier-league-3-march-2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241206103949/https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-crystal-palace-v-man-utd-premier-league-3-march-2021 |archive-date=6 December 2024 |access-date=8 September 2024 |website=Manchester United F.C.}}</ref> Henderson started the following game, the [[Manchester Derby]], which saw United win 2–0. Henderson created the second goal of the game with a halfway-line throw to [[Luke Shaw]] which saw Shaw beat his man, before a one-two with [[Marcus Rashford]] and scoring.<ref name=":1" /> De Gea returned to the UK ahead of United's next game against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]]; however, [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|pandemic]] quarantine rules and Henderson's good performances saw Henderson continue as starting goalkeeper.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jackson |first=Jamie |date=12 March 2021 |title=Manchester United's David de Gea may miss West Ham game after quarantine |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/mar/12/manchester-united-david-de-gea-may-miss-west-ham-game-after-quarantine |access-date=8 September 2024 |work=[[The Guardian]] |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Henderson started all league games in April and alternated starts in May, as did most of the squad, due to United's fixtures congestion caused by the pandemic and the [[2021 Old Trafford protests]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Fisher |first=Ben |date=6 May 2021 |title=Solskjær hits out over Manchester United's 'impossible' fixture pile-up |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/may/06/ole-gunnar-solskjaer-hits-out-over-manchester-uniteds-impossible-fixture-pileup |access-date=8 September 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Henderson made 25 starts and one substitute appearances in United's [[2020–21 Manchester United F.C. season|2020–21 season]].

During Manchester United's [[2021–22 Manchester United F.C. season|2021–22 pre-season]] Henderson caught [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite web |date=2 August 2021 |title=Dean Henderson: Covid-19 forces Manchester United goalkeeper out of training camp |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58064129 |access-date=8 September 2024 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Dawson |first=Rob |date=7 August 2021 |title=Henderson struggling with COVID effect - Ole |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/37619668/manchester-united-monitor-dean-henderson-covid-19-struggles-solskjaer |access-date=8 September 2024 |website=ESPN}}</ref> This developed into [[long COVID]], and saw Henderson out of the squad until late September when he played in United's [[2021–22 EFL Cup|League Cup]] opener, where defeat to West Ham saw them exit the competition in their first game.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mathieson |first=Stuart |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-man-utd-0-west-ham-1-in-carabao-cup-22-september-2021 |title=Report: United 0 West Ham 1 |date=22 September 2021 |access-date=8 September 2024 |website=Manchester United F.C.}}</ref> Henderson's only other domestic appearances in the 2021–22 season was the club's [[2021–22 FA Cup|FA Cup]] exit to [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Nelson |first=Joe |title=United 1 Middlesbrough 1 (7–8 on penalties) |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-united-v-middlesbrough-04-february-2022 |date=4 February 2022 |access-date=8 September 2024 |website=Manchester United F.C.}}</ref>

Failing to regain his starting place, at the end Henderson accused Manchester United of making him "sit there and waste 12 months", "not [following] through with anything they told me", and refused to play under incoming manager [[Erik Ten Hag]].<ref>{{cite news |author=The Athletic Staff |date=3 August 2022 |title=Dean Henderson on Manchester United return: 'To waste 12 months is criminal. I was fuming' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3471561/2022/08/02/dean-henderson-on-manchester-united-return/ |access-date=8 September 2024 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He was loaned to [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] the following season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dean Henderson: Nottingham Forest sign Man Utd goalkeeper on loan as Giulian Biancone also completes move |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12644246/dean-henderson-nottingham-forest-sign-manchester-united-goalkeeper-on-loan |access-date=8 September 2024 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref>

====2022–2023: Loan to Nottingham Forest====
On 2 July 2022, Henderson joined newly promoted Premier League club [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on loan for the [[2022–23 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2022–23]] season.<ref>{{cite news |title=Henderson completes season–long loan move|url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/man-utd-goalkeeper-dean-henderson-joins-nottingham-forest-on-loan|website=ManUtd.com|publisher=Manchester United|date=2 July 2022|access-date=2 July 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=2 July 2022 |title=Forest sign England international Dean Henderson |url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2022/july/02/forest-sign-england-international-dean-henderson/ |access-date=2 July 2022 |website=Nottingham Forest Football Club}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Nottingham Forest transfer news: Man Utd's Dean Henderson set to join on loan |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12639681/nottingham-forest-transfer-news-man-utds-dean-henderson-set-to-join-on-loan-after-taiwo-awoniyi-clause-met |access-date=13 April 2025 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref> In an interview with TalkSport in August 2022, Henderson criticised his parent club over his lack of game time during the previous season.<ref>{{cite news |date=2 August 2022 |title=Dean Henderson: On-loan Forest goalkeeper calls Man Utd treatment 'criminal' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62401130 |access-date=6 June 2023 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 14 August 2022, during his second appearance for the club, Henderson saved a penalty from [[Declan Rice]] and kept a clean sheet in a 1–0 win against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] as Forest won the first Premier League game played at the City Ground in 23 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62453942 |title=Nottingham Forest 1–0 West Ham |author=Simon Stone |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 August 2022 |access-date=15 August 2022}}</ref> Henderson remained the club's starting goalkeeper until he sustained a season-ending thigh injury during a 2–0 win over Leicester City on 14 January 2023.<ref>{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Paul |date=14 January 2023 |title=Dean Henderson sustains thigh injury during Nottingham Forest's win over Leicester |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4090824/2023/01/14/dean-henderson-injury-thigh/ |access-date=6 June 2023 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

===Crystal Palace===
On 31 August 2023, Henderson joined Premier League club [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on a permanent deal, signing a five-year contract,<ref>{{cite web |date=31 August 2023 |title=Dean Henderson joins Palace on long-term deal |url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/announcement/dean-henderson-joins-crystal-palace-long-term-deal/ |access-date=31 August 2023 |website=Crystal Palace F.C. |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite news |date=31 August 2023 |title=Palace sign keeper Henderson from Man Utd |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66678025 |access-date=1 September 2023}}</ref> reported to be worth £15 million, plus £5 million in add-ons.<ref name=":0" /> On 26 September, Henderson made his Palace debut against former club Manchester United in the third round of the [[2023–24 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]]. He was substituted in the 19th minute of the match with a thigh injury which kept him sidelined for over two months.<ref>{{cite news |last=Woosnam |first=Matt |date=27 September 2023 |title=Henderson sidelined with thigh injury ahead of Manchester United clash |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4903192/2023/09/27/henderson-palace-united-thigh/ |access-date=16 September 2024 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On 17 December, he made his comeback from injury in a 2–2 draw at [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], playing the full 90 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/i-loved-every-minute-it-28306235|title='I loved every minute of it': Manchester United star reflects on his time at Old Trafford|date=30 October 2023|access-date=16 September 2024|website=Manchester Evening News}}</ref> He played the team's next seven [[2023–24 Premier League|Premier League]] fixtures, before being replaced by [[Sam Johnstone]] after a 3–1 loss at home to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on 12 February 2024.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pyzdrowski |first=Matt |date=23 February 2024 |title=Dean Henderson's impact at Crystal Palace: A goalkeeper analysis |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5292609/2024/02/23/dean-henderson-crystal-palace-goalkeeper-analysis/ |access-date=16 September 2024 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> After Johnstone sustained an elbow injury while training with England on 25 March,<ref>{{cite news |last=Steinberg |first=Jacob |date=25 March 2024 |title=Gareth Southgate looks ahead to Euro 2024 with optimism |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/mar/25/england-gareth-southgate-euro-2024 |access-date=16 September 2024 |work=[[The Guardian]] |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Henderson returned to the Crystal Palace starting line-up for their 1–1 draw with Nottingham Forest five days later. He retained his place in the Palace goal for the remainder of [[2023–24 Crystal Palace F.C. season|the season]], keeping his first Premier League clean sheet for the Eagles in a 1–0 win over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Brewin |first=John |date=14 April 2024 |title=Liverpool 0–1 Crystal Palace: Premier League – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2024/apr/14/liverpool-v-crystal-palace-premier-league-live |access-date=16 September 2024 |work=the Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

Before the start of the [[2024–25 Crystal Palace F.C. season|2024–25 season]], Henderson was assigned the number 1 jersey, having worn number 30 the previous season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cdjwdk37pz2o|title=Johnstone replaced as number one by Henderson|date=13 August 2024|access-date=16 September 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Henderson played every minute of Palace's [[2025 FA Cup final]] 1–0 win over [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on 17 May 2025; after a contentious handball call in which he was not sent off for handling the ball outside of his area, he later saved a penalty from [[Omar Marmoush]] and made a number of important saves to ensure a clean sheet, dedicating the victory to his late father. He was the highest rated player of the match (rated 9.07 out of 10) by [[BBC Sport]] users.<ref name=facup/> Later that year, on 10 August, he saved two penalties during the shoot-out win over Liverpool in the [[2025 FA Community Shield|Community Shield]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Smith |first=Emma |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cy7y0p1p7ezt |title=Crystal Palace 2–2 Liverpool |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 August 2025 }}</ref> On 23 January 2026, it was confirmed that manager [[Oliver Glasner]] had appointed Henderson as [[Captain (association football)|club captain]] following the departure of [[Marc Guéhi]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-01-29 |title=Dean Henderson: Palace's No. 1 – and new captain – in his words - News |url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/features/dean-henderson-palace-feature-in-his-words/ |access-date=2026-02-09 |website=Crystal Palace F.C. |language=en-GB}}</ref>

In the 2025–26 season, as the newly appointed captain, Henderson has solidified his position as the undisputed first-choice goalkeeper, starting every Premier League match (27 appearances, 2,430 minutes played as of 22 February 2026). He has achieved 10 clean sheets, made 74 saves, and conceded 32 goals (1.19 per game average), while delivering consistent high ratings and key interventions, such as a penalty save in a recent victory over Wolverhampton Wanderers. His leadership and reliability have been instrumental for Crystal Palace in their domestic campaign and UEFA Conference League participation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/21927/Dean-Henderson/overview |title=Dean Henderson |publisher=Premier League |access-date=26 February 2026}}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth teams===
Henderson played youth international football for England at [[England national under-16 football team|under-16]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Sheffield United's Dean Henderson joins England senior squad for the first time |url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2019/oct/08/dean-henderson-called-up-to-england-squad-081019 |publisher=The Football Association |date=8 October 2019 |access-date=7 July 2023}}</ref> [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[England national under-20 football team|under-20]] and [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] levels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dean Henderson's matches |url=https://www.besoccer.com/player/matches/d-henderson-284427 |website=besoccer.com |access-date=7 July 2023}}</ref>

In late-August 2016, Henderson was called up by the England under-20 team for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/2016/september/notts-county-team-news/ |title=Notts County Team News |publisher=Grimsby Town F.C. |date=1 September 2016 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525210554/https://www.grimsby-townfc.co.uk/news/2016/september/notts-county-team-news/ |archive-date=25 May 2018 |url-status=usurped}}<br />{{cite web |title=ENGLAND UNDER-20S SQUAD SELECTED TO FACE BRAZIL |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2016/aug/25/u20s-squad-announced-for-brazil-250816 |publisher=The Football Association |date=25 August 2016 |access-date=26 May 2018}}</ref> He made his under-20 debut in a 1–1 draw against [[Brazil national under-20 football team|Brazil]] on 1 September 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=UNDER-20S PLAY OUT BEHIND-CLOSED-DOORS DRAW WITH BRAZIL |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2016/sep/01/england-under-20s-brazil-behind-closed-doors |publisher=The Football Association |date=1 September 2016 |access-date=26 May 2018}}</ref> In May 2017, he was selected in the England under-20 squad for the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |title=England announce squad for Under-20 World Cup in South Korea |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/england/story/3122492/england-announce-squad-for-under-20-world-cup-in-south-korea |publisher=ESPN |date=9 May 2017 |access-date=23 May 2017}}</ref> He made one appearance at the tournament, in a group stage match against [[Guinea national under-20 football team|Guinea]],<ref name="Soccerway"/> and was an unused substitute during England's victory against [[Venezuela national under-20 football team|Venezuela]] in [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup final|the final]].<ref name=Under20WC>{{cite news |title=Under-20 World Cup: England beat Venezuela in final |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40237981 |website=BBC Sport |date=11 June 2017 |access-date=27 August 2017}}</ref> After the match, Henderson described this an "unbelievable feeling".<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester United's Dean Henderson lifts 2017 U20s World Cup |url=http://thepeoplesperson.com/2017/06/12/manchester-uniteds-dean-henderson-lifts-2017-u20s-world-cup-183515/ |website=The Peoples Person |date=12 June 2017 |access-date=26 May 2018}}</ref>

In August 2017, Henderson was called up by the under-21 team for the first time and was an unused substitute against [[Latvia national under-21 football team|Latvia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.shrewsburytown.com/news/2017/august/henderson-called-up-by-england/ |title=Henderson called-up by England |publisher=Shrewsbury Town F.C. |date=24 August 2017 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526194306/https://www.shrewsburytown.com/news/2017/august/henderson-called-up-by-england/ |archive-date=26 May 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> He made his under-21 debut on 24 March 2018, in a [[Friendly (association football)|friendly]] at home against [[Romania national under-21 football team|Romania]], which England won 2–1.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43529730 |title=England U21 2–1 Romania U21 |website=BBC Sport |date=24 March 2018}}</ref> Henderson was named as England's number one for the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48669141 |title=England U21 1–2 France U21 |website=BBC Sport |date=18 June 2019}}</ref>

===Senior team===
On 8 October 2019, Henderson was called up to the senior [[England national football team|England]] squad for the first time by manager [[Gareth Southgate]] as a replacement for the injured [[Tom Heaton]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49980924 |title=Dean Henderson gets England call-up to replace Tom Heaton |date=8 October 2019 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=9 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=8 October 2019 |title=Whitehaven's Dean Henderson gets England senior call-up |url=https://www.newsandstar.co.uk/sport/17955365.whitehavens-dean-henderson-gets-england-senior-call-up/?ref=rss |access-date=13 April 2025 |website=News and Star}}</ref> He made his debut on 12 November 2020, when he came on at half-time to replace [[Nick Pope (footballer)|Nick Pope]] in a 3–0 win over the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] in a friendly.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54819958 |title=England 3–0 Republic of Ireland |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=12 November 2020 |access-date=12 November 2020}}</ref>

Henderson was named as a member of England's 26-man squad for the delayed [[UEFA Euro 2020]] and was allocated the number 13 shirt. However, he withdrew due to a hip injury after the first game and was replaced by [[Aaron Ramsdale]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57480270 |title=Euro 2020: Aaron Ramsdale replaces injured Dean Henderson in England squad |website=BBC Sport |date=15 June 2021 |access-date=15 June 2021}}</ref> England ultimately lost the [[UEFA Euro 2020 final|final]] to [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and finished as runners-up.<ref name="Euro2020Final">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51198762|title=England lose shootout in Euro 2020 final |first=Phil |last=McNulty|work=BBC Sport |date=11 July 2021 |access-date=7 July 2023}}</ref>

Henderson was named in England's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cv22menk7dno |title=Eze & Wharton named in England squad for Euro 2024 |website=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2024 |access-date=6 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McNicholas |first=James |date=8 June 2024 |title=England's Euro 2024 squad: Players' shock at no Grealish, Maguire out, Shaw gamble |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5546903/2024/06/07/grealish-maguire-england-squad-decisions/ |access-date=13 April 2025 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

On 13 October 2024, Henderson made his first start for England in a 3–1 away victory against [[Finland national football team|Finland]] in the [[UEFA Nations League]] which was his first England appearance since 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/dean-henderson-england-crystal-palace-nations-league-jordan-pickford-b2629187.html |title=Dean Henderson chartered flight so family could watch his first England start |first=Jonathan |last=Veal |website=The Independent |date=14 October 2024 |access-date=14 October 2024}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Henderson is known for his distribution with both his hands and feet as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], as well as his ability to claim crosses or to catch and punch high balls, with Rob Dawson of ''[[ESPN]]'' describing him as "more complete" than his teammate [[David de Gea]] in 2021. Mark Critchley of ''[[The Independent]]'' has also described him as a "vocal presence" in goal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/manchester-united/story/4347491/man-uniteds-big-decisions-what-to-do-with-pogba-henderson-or-de-gea |title=Man United's big decisions: What to do with Pogba? Henderson or De Gea? |publisher=ESPN |last1=Dawson |first1=Rob |date=31 March 2021 |access-date=4 April 2021}}</ref><ref name="De Gea and Henderson">{{cite news |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-united-de-gea-henderson-19896184 |title=Man United fans identify difference between David de Gea and Dean Henderson |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |last1=Jackson |first1=Elliott |date=23 February 2021 |access-date=4 April 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/manchester-united/david-de-gea-dean-henderson-b1816480.html |title=David de Gea vs Dean Henderson: Manchester United's biggest dilemma near final decision |newspaper=The Independent |last1=Critchley |first1=Mark |date=14 March 2021 |access-date=4 April 2021}}</ref> He is also known for his reflexes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/liamcanning/2020/11/30/dean-henderson-is-manchester-uniteds-future-number-one/?sh=712dc87b163b |title=Dean Henderson, Nipping At David De Gea's Heels, Is Manchester United's Future No. 1 |website=Forbes |last1=Canning |first1=Liam |date=30 November 2020 |access-date=4 April 2021}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Henderson was born in [[Whitehaven]], Cumbria.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/dean-henderson-251402/ |title=Dean Henderson |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref> He played county cricket as a schoolboy and was an accomplished batsman and wicket-keeper but chose football.<ref name="Henderson 2">{{cite web |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Features/2016/Feb/focus-on-manchester-united-goalkeeper-dean-henderson-with-video-highlights.aspx |title=INTRODUCING... UNITED KEEPER DEAN HENDERSON |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=20 February 2016 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526170444/http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Features/2016/Feb/focus-on-manchester-united-goalkeeper-dean-henderson-with-video-highlights.aspx |archive-date=26 May 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Henderson initially started out as an outfield player before switching to his role as a goalkeeper.<ref>{{cite web |last=Otway |first=Jack |date=3 February 2017 |title=Manchester United Uncovered: Five things you need to know about Dean Henderson |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/762729/Manchester-United-News-Dean-Henderson-injury-Jose-Mourinho-Grimsby-Town |access-date=26 May 2018 |website=[[Daily Express]]}}</ref>

During his time at Shrewsbury Town, Henderson [[Head shaving|shaved]] off all of his hair in support of Hope House children's hospice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.shrewsburytown.com/news/2017/december/henderson-supports-hope-house/ |title=Henderson supports Hope House |publisher=Shrewsbury Town F.C. |date=15 December 2017 |access-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526201640/https://www.shrewsburytown.com/news/2017/december/henderson-supports-hope-house/ |archive-date=26 May 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 27 May 2019, Henderson achieved two Guinness World Records titles for 'Fastest time to dress as a goalkeeper (football)' (49.51 seconds) and 'Most football headed passes in one minute (team of two)' (91 – with [[Jake Clarke-Salter]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/571021-most-football-soccer-headed-passes-in-one-minute-team-of-two |title=Most football (soccer) headed passes in one minute (team of two) |date=27 May 2019 |publisher=Guinness World Records}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yjZo3qsHP6w |title=Young Lions Guinness World Record Challenge &#124; Sessegnon, Henderson & Clarke-Salter &#124; England U21 |date=7 August 2019 |via=YouTube}}</ref>

On 15 December 2025 Henderson's daughter was born.

